Agrippa says it is easier to get cursed by looking at an "evil eye" with the edge of your vision, which is more vulnerable to penetration; looking at the one who tries to curse you straight renders you immune, as "light meets light" - this is also how romantic love is ignited.

Also the folk belief that "any curse eventually returns back to the sorcerer" might be a bit misguided, as Agrippa explains that to curse someone, his own soul has to already be diseased by the curse he wishes to inflict

Plinius tells a story about a boy who exhausted from the heat of the road went into a cave and slept for 57 years, leaving unchanged. Ray Peat talks about how construction workers sometimes find frogs that have been hibernating for 100+ years in a building's foundations.

According to Dr. Peat it has to do with the levels of CO2 in the hibernating organism increasing, allowing it to enter a permanent state where it does not age, move, burn calories, etc. I guess the Plinius stories (and other similar ones) being always in CAVES might be a clue.
